      {
        "id": 4116,
        "name": "Meng Xu",
        "username": "mengxu",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/forums.foundationdb.org/mengxu/{size}/893_2.png",
        "created_at": "2019-05-17T05:45:07.314Z",
        "cooked": "<aside class=\"quote no-group\" data-username=\"alloc\" data-post=\"1\" data-topic=\"1367\">\n<div class=\"title\">\n<div class=\"quote-controls\"></div>\n<img loading=\"lazy\" alt=\"\" width=\"24\" height=\"24\" src=\"https://sea1.discourse-cdn.com/foundationdb/user_avatar/forums.foundationdb.org/alloc/48/9_2.png\" class=\"avatar\"> alloc:</div>\n<blockquote>\n<p>A \u201cget committed transaction size\u201d API that can only be called after a transaction has been committed. This would allow someone who\u2019s doing a bunch of work to then inspect how big their already committed transaction was. Then if the transaction exceeds some value, they can themselves apply a limit to do less work in the <em>next</em> transaction. This is obviously less good then knowing before one commits (or before one adds more work), but it might be easier to implement as the transaction already has to calculate its size before it commits, so it would then be as simple as just \u201cremembering\u201d what the value was.</p>\n</blockquote>\n</aside>\n<p>A dummy question:<br>\nIs the transaction handler destroyed immediately after commit?<br>\nIf yes, how do we get the transaction info. after commit?<br>\nIf no, when is a transaction handler destroyed?</p>",
